{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Electrical Power",
      "simpleDefinition": "The rate at which electrical energy is converted into another form, such as heat or light.",
      "anchor": "Think of it as the 'work rate' of the circuit, measured in Watts (W).",
      "misconception": "Confusing power with energy; power is how fast work is done, while energy is the total amount of work done over time."
    },
    {
      "term": "Thermal Effect",
      "simpleDefinition": "The heat produced when an electric current flows through a material that has resistance.",
      "anchor": "The glowing element in an electric heater or the wire in a toaster.",
      "misconception": "Believing heat in a circuit is always a 'fault'; it is often the intended purpose, such as in an immersion heater."
    },
    {
      "term": "Chemical Effect",
      "simpleDefinition": "The process where an electric current causes a chemical change when passing through a liquid solution.",
      "anchor": "Charging a car battery or the process of electroplating jewelry.",
      "misconception": "Thinking that electricity only travels through solid metal wires and cannot move through liquids."
    },
    {
      "term": "Electrolyte",
      "simpleDefinition": "A liquid or gel that conducts electricity through chemical action, typically found in batteries.",
      "anchor": "The acid solution inside a lead-acid battery.",
      "misconception": "Assuming all liquids conduct electricity; only those that can be chemically broken down (electrolytes) do so in this context."
    },
    {
      "term": "Total Power (Pt)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The sum of all individual power used by components in a circuit.",
      "anchor": "Adding the wattage of every lightbulb in a room to find the total load.",
      "misconception": "Thinking power is calculated differently for series and parallel circuits; unlike resistance, you always add individual power values to get the total."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Power is the rate of doing work.",
    "Total power is the sum of all individual powers.",
    "Thermal effect means heat generation.",
    "Chemical effect means battery charging or electrolysis.",
    "P = I x V is the primary power formula."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Power and energy are interchangeable terms.",
    "Power adds up differently in series than it does in parallel.",
    "Electric current only produces heat and has no other physical effects.",
    "You can ignore the chemical effect when discussing DC battery systems."
  ]
}

[
  {
    "key": "202-4d-teach-check-1",
    "title": "Power in DC Circuits",
    "objective": "Calculate power in series and parallel D.C. circuits using standard formulas.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Electrical Power is the rate at which electrical energy is converted into another form, such as heat or light. Think of it as the 'work rate' of the circuit, measured in Watts (W). To calculate power, we use the primary formula: Power (P) = Current (I) x Voltage (V). This tells us how much work is being done every second.",
      "In many practical scenarios, you might not have all three values. If you only know the current and the resistance, you use the formula P = I² x R. If you only know the voltage and the resistance, you use P = V² / R. These formulas allow you to determine the power load of any component in a DC system.",
      "A critical rule for electricians is that Total Power (Pt) is always the sum of all individual power used by components in a circuit. Whether the resistors are connected in series or parallel, you simply add the individual wattages together to find the total load. For example, three 100W lamps will always draw 300W in total. Correctly calculating this total power is essential for selecting the right cable sizes and protective devices to prevent overheating."
    ],
    "hint": "Remember that regardless of whether the circuit is series or parallel, you always add the individual power values to find the total."
  },
  {
    "key": "202-4d-teach-check-2",
    "title": "Chemical and Thermal Effects",
    "objective": "Identify and describe the chemical and thermal effects produced by electric current.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "When electric current flows through a circuit, it produces physical changes. The Thermal Effect is the heat produced when current flows through a material that has resistance. This is the 'work' being done by the electrons as they collide with the atoms of the conductor. We use this effect intentionally in devices like the glowing element of an electric heater, a toaster, or an immersion heater. However, it also explains why standard cables warm up; if the power is too high, this thermal effect can damage insulation.",
      "The Chemical Effect occurs when an electric current passes through a liquid solution known as an electrolyte. This process, called electrolysis, causes a chemical change in the liquid. You see this effect in action when charging or discharging a lead-acid battery, where electrical energy is converted into chemical energy for storage. It is also used in electroplating to coat metals. It is a common misconception that current only produces heat; the chemical changes in batteries are just as vital for DC systems. Understanding these effects helps you identify how different electrical components function and the risks associated with current flow."
    ],
    "hint": "Think of the thermal effect as heat in a wire and the chemical effect as the process inside a charging battery."
  }
]

