      "title": "Power in DC Circuits",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What is the primary formula used to calculate electrical power when current and voltage are known?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "P = I x V",
            "Power equals current multiplied by voltage",
            "Watts = Amps x Volts"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "In a DC circuit, how is the total power (Pt) determined regardless of whether the components are in series or parallel?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Total power is the sum of all individual powers",
            "Add the wattage of every component together",
            "Pt = P1 + P2 + P3..."
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the standard unit of measurement for electrical power?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Watts",
            "W",
            "The rate of doing work"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Explain why the total power in a circuit is always the sum of individual component powers, even if the circuit configuration changes from series to parallel.",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Power represents the total rate of energy conversion in the whole circuit",
        "Every component consumes energy regardless of how it is connected",
        "The total work done by the source must equal the sum of work done by all loads",
        "Circuit arrangement affects current and voltage distribution but not the additive nature of power"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about the 'work rate' of the circuit and the primary formula P=IV."
    },
    {
      "title": "Chemical and Thermal Effects",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What is the name of the effect where current produces heat as it passes through a conductor with resistance?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Thermal effect",
            "Heating effect",
            "Heat generation in a resistor"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What effect is occurring when an electric current causes a chemical change in a liquid solution, such as during battery charging?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Chemical effect",
            "Electrolysis",
            "Chemical action"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What specific term describes the liquid or gel that conducts electricity through chemical action in a battery?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Electrolyte",
            "Conductive liquid solution",
            "Battery acid or gel"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "How does the thermal effect of current dictate the maximum power rating of an electrical component like a resistor or a cable?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Current flow generates heat based on the resistance (P=I²R)",
        "Components have a physical limit on how much heat they can dissipate safely",
        "Exceeding the power rating causes the thermal effect to become destructive",
        "Excessive heat can melt insulation or damage the material structure of the component"
      ],
      "hint": "Consider what happens to the temperature of a wire as the power (wattage) increases."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Power, Heat, and Safety",
    "objective": "Synthesize power calculation skills with the understanding of thermal effects to explain why exceeding a circuit's power rating is a fire risk.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Electrical Power (P) is the rate at which energy is converted into heat or chemical change.",
      "The Thermal Effect is the heat produced when current flows through a resistance.",
      "Total Power (Pt) in any DC circuit is the sum of the power used by all components.",
      "Formula: P = V² / R or P = I²R."
    ],
    "questionText": "A DC heating circuit consists of a 20Ω heating element connected to a 100V DC supply. \n\n1) Calculate the total power (P) produced by the element. \n2) Identify the specific physical effect occurring in the element. \n3) Explain, using the relationship between power and heat, why installing a cable only rated for 200W in this circuit would create a fire hazard.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Power Calculation: P = V² / R = 100² / 20 = 10,000 / 20 = 500W.",
      "Physical Effect: Thermal effect (heat generation).",
      "Safety Explanation: The circuit produces 500W of power as heat, but the cable is only rated to safely dissipate 200W. This mismatch means the cable will overheat, potentially melting the insulation and causing a fire."
    ],
    "hint": "Start by using the voltage and resistance to find the wattage. Once you have the 500W figure, compare it to the 200W cable rating and think about the 'Thermal Effect' on the cable insulation."
  }
}

